04438nam a22006015i 9780691226507DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2021944063  a97806912265077 a10.1515/97806912265072doi  a(DE-B1597)585506  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSOC0260002bisacsh1 aDeutschmann, Emanuel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMapping the Transnational World :bHow We Move and Communicate across Borders, and Why It Matters /cEmanuel Deutschmann. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b5 color + 29 b/w illus. 16 tables. 3 maps.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in Global and Comparative Sociology00tFrontmatter -- tSummary of Contents -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- t1 Entering the Transnational World -- t2. Four Paths toward a Comparative Sociology of Regional Integration -- t3. The Regionalized Structure of Transnational Human Activity, 1960–2010 -- t4. Why Does Regionalism Occur in Transnational Human Activity? -- t5.The Spatial Structure of Transnational Human Activity -- t6. Lessons: Mobilization, Not Globalization -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA study in the structure, growth, and future of transnational human travel and communicationDuring the past decades, humanity has become more transnationally active. Increasingly, people travel and communicate across borders. Yet, we still know little about the overall structure of this transnational world. Is it really a fully globalized world in which everything is linked, as popular catchphrases like “global village” suggest? Through a sweeping comparative analysis of eight types of mobility and communication among countries worldwide—from migration and tourism to Facebook friendships and phone calls—Mapping the Transnational World demonstrates that our behavior is actually regionalized, not globalized.Emanuel Deutschmann shows that transnational activity within world regions is not so much the outcome of political, cultural, or economic factors, but driven primarily by geographic distance. He explains that the spatial structure of transnational human activity follows a simple mathematical function, the power law, a pattern that also fits the movements of many other animal species on this planet. Moreover, this pattern remains extremely stable during the five decades studied—1960 to 2010. Unveiling proximity-induced regionalism as a major feature of planet-scale networks of transnational human activity, Deutschmann provides a crucial corrective to several fields of research.Revealing why a truly global society is unlikely to emerge, Mapping the Transnational World highlights the essential role of interaction beyond borders on a planet that remains spatially fragmented.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073912140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978069122650740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691226507423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691226507/original  a978-3-11-073912-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK